The Herald-Tribune of March 22, 1939, page 21, carries an article
stating that this structure and the adjoining buildings to the east,
comprising the lower half of this block (all owned by the Collegiate
Reformed Protestant Church since 1664) are to be demolished and their
sites improved with a modern 7 story office building. This will be
erected by the Ueorge A. Fuller Co. and completed in 1941 for the use
of the wetna Casualty and Surety Co. and its' affiliates. It will
front 150 feet on Fulton wt., 120 feet on .:illiam St., and about 150
feet on Ann St. An investment of ~4,O00,O0O is involved; the church
receiving '3,000,O00 in rent during the life of a lease, which is for
21 years with two renewals, a total of 63 years.
Thie building shown here is the oldest of the group and was erected
abot 1855, directly after the congregation had moved to the Marble
Collegiate Church (1651-4) at the N. W. corner of Fifth Avenue and
W. 29th Street. The Fulton Street Prayer Meeting has met here since
their organization in September 1857.
